    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "that seems a bit narrow though. what if the \"geopolitical interest\" was actually about preventing a humanitarian catastrophe on a massive scale? if the intervention stops a genocide, doesn't that inherently make it a success in terms of international norms and global stability, regardless of what happens with the government afterwards? it feels like you're prioritizing state borders and power vacuums over the actual human cost.",
